 Al-Naji began designing BitClout, a web and application-based social media=
 platform with an interface that promised to be a =E2=80=9Cnew type of soci=
al network that mixes speculation and social media.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p> =
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BitClout=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CWhite Paper=E2=80=
=9D (marketing materials that described the BitClout project) touted BitClo=
ut as =E2=80=9Clike Bitcoin=E2=80=9D because it was =E2=80=9Ca fully open-s=
ource project=E2=80=9D with =E2=80=9Cno company behind it =E2=80=93 it=E2=
=80=99s just coins and code.=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The =
White Paper further explained that BTCLT would be the native token=C2=A0of =
the BitClout project.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to documen=
ts prepared by Al-Naji in conjunction with the BitClout project, the price =
of BTCLT would automatically double for every million BTCLT sold directly f=
rom the BitClout platform, with Al-Naji reserving two million BTCLT for him=
self as the project=E2=80=99s founder.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Al-Naji explained that purchasing BTCLT through the BitClout platform in=
volved a =E2=80=9Ctotally decentralized=E2=80=9D so-called =E2=80=9Catomic =
swap=E2=80=9D whereby investors would deposit the crypto asset bitcoin into=
 BitClout=E2=80=99s treasury wallet and receive BTCLT in exchange.</p> <p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This exchange, however, only operated in one direc=
tion, meaning that BTCLT investors could not exchange their tokens back int=
o bitcoin or fiat currency (e.g., U.S. dollars) via the BitClout platform. =
This fact was not explained in the BitClout White Paper.</p> <p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Al-Naji privately explained to an early investor that he vie=
wed this technical limitation as a positive feature of the platform because=
 restricting the ability to sell BTCLT had the effect of driving up its pri=
ce.</p> </blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right=3F Here=E2=80=99s =
a thing. It costs $1. If you buy one, the next one will cost $2. If someone=
 buys it, the next one will cost $4. Et cetera. The price of the thing alwa=
ys goes up, leaving every buyer (except the most recent one) with a large g=
uaranteed profit. Of course they can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>sell=C2=A0</em>the =
thing to realize the profit, but that too is a benefit: If they can=E2=80=
=99t sell, the price can=E2=80=99t go down.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 1=
