minor point from the Google case. If you work at certain sorts of companies=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0including Google and many financial services firms =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you will subtly or unsubtly be taught a lesson about emailing. The=
 lesson is that, if you are up to no good, you should (1) cc a lawyer on al=
l your emails and (2) write =E2=80=9CPRIVILEGED AND CONFIDENTIAL=E2=80=9D a=
t the top of them.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The theory is that this=
 is a magic incantation: If one day your company gets sued or investigated =
for whatever bad stuff you are up to, the plaintiffs or investigators will =
ask for your emails, and you will have to hand them over,=C2=A0<em>except=
=C2=A0</em>the ones that are protected by attorney-client privilege. If you=
 are asking your lawyer for advice, that is privileged and does not have to=
 be handed over. Whereas if you are just emailing your boss to say =E2=80=
=9Cshould we do these crimes,=E2=80=9D that is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>privi=
leged, and the investigators get to read that.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The above two paragraphs =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the rest of this section, =
for that matter =E2=80=94=C2=A0are very much not legal advice, and this the=
ory is not really right. Copying lawyers and writing =E2=80=9CPRIV &amp; CO=
NF=E2=80=9D at the top of emails is more a matter of superstition than it i=
s a correct legal analysis, it probably won=E2=80=99t help you much, and it=
 might annoy a judge. As it annoyed the judge here, who wrote (citations om=
itted):</p> <blockquote> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Google trained its em=
ployees to add its in-house lawyers on =E2=80=9Cany written communication r=
egarding Rev Share [RSA] and MADA.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0It also instructed that, w=
hen =E2=80=9Cdealing with a sensitive issue=E2=80=9D via email, to =E2=80=
=9Censure the email communication is privileged=E2=80=9D employees could ad=
d a =E2=80=9Clawyer in [the] =E2=80=98to=E2=80=99 field,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
mark =E2=80=98Attorney/Client Privileged,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cask the law=
yer a question.=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Google employees =
assiduously followed that advice. As a result, Google=E2=80=99s outside cou=
nsel in this case initially withheld tens of thousands=C2=A0records on the =
grounds of privilege, which ultimately were re-reviewed, deemed not privile=
ged, and produced to Plaintiffs. This creation of faux privileged materials=
, Plaintiffs contend, =E2=80=9Cdemonstrates that Google intended to harm co=
mpetition through its contracting practices and its supposed procompetitive=
 justifications were simply pretext.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p> </blockquote> <p st=
